Vlad F 20-Jun-19 06:18 PM
b) a while-loop and an if statement if statements are statements that are meant to execute lines of code below it, under the condition that has to be met. Ex. â€œif words==8:â€, which says that if the value of words is equal to 8, then it will execute the following code and if not, then it will pass through it. While loops act similarly, but inherently differently. While loops are meant to act as an infinite if statement, and it has the same condition requirements, but the difference is that it will execute the code in a literal endless loop, until itâ€™s condition is broken or the code is stopped.
c) string and list Strings are immutable, meaning they cannot have their values changed, while lists are free for customization. Lists can have values that are either integers, floats, and/or strings. Lists also have many built-in functions for them, such as sorted(), max(), min(), and more.
d) mutable and immutable data types Mutable data types are data types that can be changed and are not fixed. Immutable data types are, logically, the opposite. A good example of a mutable data type is a list which can be changed in order, specific values, and be shortened/lengthened to the userâ€™s liking. However, a good immutable data type example is the tuple, which cannot have any attributes added or removed from it. The difference between these two is that they are opposites, in the sense of customization.
f) programs with classes and programs without classes programs with classes can leave a lot of the code out of the main loop and have everything be cleaner and shorter there. They also require a separate document for the main loops to be clean as well, which will make the person understanding it have an easier time. Programs without classes, however, clutter the main loops and make it very hard to understand what is going on in them, even with proper sectioning. This can also cause a slew of problems for later tasks, such as intro and game-over screens for functions without classes, which will be difficult to do without any classes, let alone functions.
